    "ID": "toss1e1",
    "Title": "The Man Trap",
    "Series": "TOS",
    "Season": 1,
    "Episode": 1,
    "KeyCharacters": [
      "James T. Kirk",
      "Spock",
      "Leonard McCoy",
      "Nyota Uhura"
    ],
    "GuestCharacters": [
      "Nancy Crater",
      "Professor Robert Crater",
      "Crewman Darnell"
    ],
    "Antagonists": [
      "M-113 Creature (Salt Vampire)"
    ],
    "StorySections": [
      {
        "Header": "Teaser",
        "Text": "The Enterprise visits planet M-113 to provide routine medical exams for archaeologist Robert Crater and his wife Nancy, who was once romantically involved with McCoy. Kirk teases McCoy about seeing his old flame again as they beam down with Crewman Darnell. Each of the men perceives Nancy differently\u2014McCoy sees the young woman he remembers, Kirk sees a woman of appropriate age, and Darnell sees an alluring blonde. The odd disparity goes unexplained as Nancy lures Darnell outside, where he is soon found dead with strange marks on his face and no clear cause of death."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act I",
        "Text": "Back aboard the ship, McCoy insists Darnell died of natural causes, but Spock notes the absence of salt in the dead man's body. Kirk becomes suspicious of the Craters' evasive behavior, especially when Robert demands that they leave only salt tablets and depart. The landing party returns to the surface to search for answers, only to have another crewman killed in similarly mysterious fashion. Kirk orders the Craters brought in for questioning, while an unknown intruder\u2014taking on the form of various crew members\u2014secretly beams aboard the Enterprise."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act II",
        "Text": "As deaths continue, the intruder adopts the appearance of familiar faces to get close to victims and drain their bodies of salt. Spock's investigation confirms the pattern: every corpse is completely devoid of sodium, and the murders coincide with sightings of people who should not be present. Kirk and Spock track down Professor Crater, who finally admits that his real wife died years earlier and that the last surviving native of M-113 has been living with him, using its shape-shifting ability to appear as Nancy. Crater compares the creature to an endangered animal, claiming it needs salt to live and deserves protection."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act III",
        "Text": "Kirk beams Crater and the creature\u2014now disguised as McCoy\u2014to the ship, hoping to contain the threat. In a tense confrontation, the being refuses to reveal its true form, and Crater resists efforts to identify it, still pleading for its survival. When the creature kills Crater and nearly drains Spock, its inhuman strength and predatory nature become impossible to ignore. Kirk confronts it in McCoy's quarters with salt tablets and a phaser, trying to force a choice between feeding and fleeing, but McCoy hesitates, still seeing the woman he once loved."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Tag",
        "Text": "The creature finally reveals its natural, monstrous appearance as it attacks Kirk, desperately trying to draw the salt from his body. Spock's attempts to physically subdue it fail, leaving McCoy to make the final decision: he fires his phaser, killing the last of the M-113 beings despite its pleas in Nancy's voice. On the bridge, Kirk reflects on the extinction of a unique lifeform, likening it to the buffalo of Earth's past and acknowledging that survival sometimes demands tragic choices. The Enterprise leaves orbit, having preserved its crew at the cost of erasing an entire species from the galaxy."
      }
    ],
    "EthicalIssues": [
      "Whether an intelligent but dangerous last-of-its-kind creature should be preserved or destroyed when it preys on sentient beings for survival.",
      "Crater's decision to conceal the truth and enable further deaths in order to protect the creature he empathizes with.",
      "The tension between McCoy's personal feelings for Nancy and his duty as a Starfleet officer when the creature must be stopped."
    ],
    "ContinuityNotes": [
      "Introduces McCoy's romantic past and hints at the emotional life he had before joining Starfleet.",
      "Reinforces Starfleet's practice of performing routine medical and resupply checks on remote outposts.",
      "Establishes a recurring Trek motif where apparently monstrous aliens are revealed to have understandable motives."
    ],
    "ThematicNotes": [
      "Nostalgia and illusion\u2014McCoy's memory of Nancy blinds him to the threat in front of him.",
      "The cost of survival, both for individuals and species, when resources like salt become scarce.",
      "The danger of idealizing the past and refusing to accept painful change."
    ],
    "BehindTheScenes": [
      "Although produced later in the schedule, this was the first episode of Star Trek ever broadcast, chosen for its accessible monster-story structure.",
      "The 'salt vampire' costume became one of the series' most memorable creature designs despite limited effects technology.",
      "The episode helped define Trek's balance of horror, mystery, and character-driven drama in its early weeks on the air."
    ]
