      {
        "Header": "Teaser",
        "Text": "The Enterprise arrives at the frozen world of Psi 2000 to recover a research team and monitor the planet's disintegration. Spock and junior officer Joe Tormolen beam down in environmental suits, only to find the scientists dead in bizarre, irrational positions\u2014as if they simply stopped caring about survival. Despite strict procedures, Tormolen briefly removes his glove and contacts a strange red contaminant on a control surface. Back on the ship, he appears physically healthy, but something unseen has already begun to spread."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act I",
        "Text": "Tormolen becomes increasingly agitated in the rec room, ranting about humanity's right to meddle with the cosmos and turning a dinner conversation into a near-violent confrontation. He lashes out at Sulu and Riley with a knife before stabbing himself, dying despite McCoy's best efforts. Soon other crew members start acting out their deepest impulses: Sulu dashes through the corridors with a fencing foil, playing at swashbuckler, while Riley locks himself in Engineering and sings over the intercom. Spock realizes that an infection is lowering inhibitions and amplifying buried emotions, threatening the ship's ability to function."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act II",
        "Text": "Riley's antics in Engineering disrupt critical systems, shutting down environmental controls and endangering the ship as it orbits an increasingly unstable planet. Spock, infected himself, struggles not to succumb to his own repressed feelings about his human mother and Vulcan upbringing, breaking down in front of Nurse Chapel. Kirk fights the effects of the contagion as it magnifies his fear of losing the Enterprise and being trapped in a desk-bound career on Earth. McCoy races to identify the nature of the infection, realizing that altered water molecules are acting like a form of intoxication with far more dangerous consequences."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act III",
        "Text": "With systems failing and Psi 2000 tearing itself apart below, Scotty and the engineering team attempt a risky restart of the Enterprise's engines. McCoy finally develops a cure and begins administering it, gradually restoring sanity to the crew, including Spock and Kirk. To escape the planet's gravity and impending destruction, Scotty implements an unprecedented cold restart of the warp engines, overshooting in a way that slingshots the Enterprise backward through time. The ship survives, leaving the crew briefly stunned by the realization that they have accidentally discovered a crude form of time travel."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Tag",
        "Text": "As the Enterprise stabilizes in a safe orbit and normal time, Kirk and Spock calculate that the ship has traveled several days into its own past. They speculate lightly about the possibilities of time travel, while agreeing that meddling with history would be unwise. The crew resumes normal operations, a little embarrassed by the uninhibited behavior many of them displayed while infected. Kirk orders a course set for their next mission, leaving Psi 2000 and its tragic research team behind as a cautionary tale."
      }
    ],
    "EthicalIssues": [
      "The risks inherent in poorly understood exploratory missions and how much danger is acceptable in pursuit of knowledge.",
      "Responsibility for actions committed under the influence of an external agent that amplifies latent desires and fears.",
      "The moral implications of time travel, even when discovered accidentally, and whether it should ever be used deliberately."
