      "Android Korby"
    ],
    "StorySections": [
      {
        "Header": "Teaser",
        "Text": "The Enterprise travels to the icy planet Exo III in response to a long-silent signal from Dr. Roger Korby, a famed medical researcher and Christine Chapel's missing fianc\u00e9. Chapel, now serving as a nurse aboard the Enterprise, is both hopeful and anxious about the possibility that Korby has survived. Korby insists that only a small landing party beam down, asking specifically for Kirk and Chapel and refusing to come up to the ship. The caution and secrecy surrounding his request immediately puts Kirk on alert."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act I",
        "Text": "On the surface, Kirk and Chapel find a seemingly deserted environment but are led into an underground complex carved from the planet's frozen crust. They are greeted not by a full research team but by a small group including the imposing, stone-faced figure Ruk and the beautiful, enigmatic Andrea. Korby explains that he has discovered the remnants of an ancient android-manufacturing civilization and has been perfecting their techniques. Kirk becomes uneasy when Korby delays contact with the Enterprise and downplays the absence of his original colleagues."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act II",
        "Text": "Korby reveals that he has transferred some of his knowledge\u2014and possibly more\u2014into android bodies, claiming this is the next step in human evolution. He demonstrates a duplication process by creating an android copy of Kirk, complete with implanted memories and mannerisms. The real Kirk fights to maintain his sense of identity and slips a verbal cue into the replica's programming to alert Spock later. Chapel is horrified as she realizes that Korby's obsession with perfectibility may have pushed him beyond recognizable humanity."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act III",
        "Text": "Ruk, one of the original Exo III androids, begins to recall that his makers destroyed themselves through similar attempts at controlling life, turning on them in self-defense. Confronted with this history, Ruk rebels against Korby, seeing him as no different from the long-dead Old Ones, and is ultimately destroyed in the ensuing struggle. Kirk presses Korby, who finally admits that his current body is entirely artificial and that only his memories and sense of self remain from the original man. Faced with Chapel's horror and his own realization that his plans would impose a dehumanizing 'perfection' on others, Korby destroys himself and Andrea, ending the experiment."
      },
