      },
      {
        "Header": "Act I",
        "Text": "In Stratos, High Advisor Plasus offers hospitality and assures Kirk that zenite shipments will resume, blaming delays on Troglyte terrorism. Kirk meets Droxine, Plasus's sheltered daughter, who is fascinated by Spock's logical mind and romantically intrigued by him. Meanwhile, Vanna, leader of the Troglyte dissidents, is captured and brought to Stratos, where Plasus plans to torture her for information."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act II",
        "Text": "McCoy's analysis reveals that unrefined zenite emits a gas that impairs reasoning and heightens aggression in anyone exposed, explaining the volatility among the miners. Kirk argues that the Troglytes suffer both physical and social damage while the cloud-dwelling elites remain literally and figuratively above the pollution. Plasus refuses to acknowledge this, insisting on Troglyte inferiority and maintaining the status quo through force."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Act III",
        "Text": "Kirk engineers an escape with Vanna to the mines, intending to demonstrate the effects of zenite gas on all parties. He forcibly brings Plasus into the mine as well, exposing everyone to the gas until the High Advisor's own irrational rage proves the Troglytes' condition is environmental, not innate. Faced with the truth and the threat of Federation withdrawal, Plasus reluctantly agrees to improved working conditions and the use of filter masks for miners."
      },
      {
        "Header": "Tag",
        "Text": "Vanna remains wary but accepts the possibility of negotiated reform rather than violent revolt, while Droxine expresses a new awareness of the suffering beneath her city. As the Enterprise departs with the needed zenite, Kirk and Spock reflect on societies divided by artificial hierarchies\u2014and on how difficult it can be to change a culture that literally lives in the clouds."
      }
